Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the second innings! Around 10 overs remaining in Day's play but with the time running away, this is a very short session South Africa have to play out. Dean Elgar and Aiden Markram will open the batting. Jasprit Bumrah will begin with the ball. Here we go...
... Second Innings ...

Elgar will be very happy with how his bowlers performed. Everyone chipped in a wicket at least and showed consistency throughout the innings. Kagiso Rabada and Duanne Olivier were the picks from the bowlers as they scalped 4 and 3 wickets respectively. Kagiso Rabada was so good all over today. He bowled in the channel outside off and kept Kohli low and away from scoring any runs freely. The contest between Kagiso Rabada and Virat Kohli was worth a penny as both showed determination in their respective platform.

Lungi Ngidi takes the last wicket and folds things out. Gutted for Kohli who fought hard to reach to his century but fell trying to up the ante. Also, there was no support from the other end for him means India end their innings at 223. After the wicket of Rishabh Pant, the flood gates opened and South Africa did well to not let the tail-enders wag much and bundled India out. Things could have been different if someone had supported the skipper from the other end but that is a story for another day.

OUT! TAKEN! Length ball, outside off. Shami cuts it straight to point where Bavuma takes a sharp low catch. It is taken upstairs to check if it is clean and the umpire says no conclusive evidence is there. India are all out at 223.
Commentary.Howout: c Temba Bavuma b Lungi Ngidi

Umesh Yadav continues to throw his bat it! Another length ball, outside off. Umesh Yadav swings and misses.

Another shorter ball, around middle. Umesh Yadav does well to get away from that one.

Dean Elgar, from first slip goes behind the second slip fielder takes a good catch. Kohli was not giving the strike to Bumrah off Rabada but he trusted his partner to face the last two deliveries and Bumrah perished here.

We are back for the final session of Day 1! The players are out in the middle. Virat Kohli and Rishabh Pant will resume their batting. Lungi Ngidi will begin with the ball. Here we go...
... Day 1, Session 3 ...

Cheteshwar Pujara and Virat Kohli started the session off well, but Pujara could not hold on for too long and was dismissed for a well-made 43. Ajinkya Rahane fell cheaply once again to a ripper by Rabada. Virat Kohli has been exceptional in the middle, he is displaying his class at the moment. He has been patient and not getting very tempted. As long as he is at the crease, India could surely cross the 200 mark with ease at the end of the play. Pant too, has been showing determination and will be looking forward to carry on the same way in the final session. The third session will start at 7 pm IST (1:30 pm GMT). Do join us for the same.

That was an exciting session of Test cricket! South Africa would be the happier side, cause they managed to pick up another two wickets in the session. They have been disciplined with their line and lengths, and not allowing the batters to score quickly. Kagiso Rabada has been phenomenal, he has troubled the Indian skipper, on multiple occasions, but Virat Kohli has survived through everything.

Review! South Africa have reviewed a caught behind decision! The replay rolls in. UltraEdge confirms there is no spike as the ball passes the bat. Okay, there was a murmur as the ball went past the bat. South Africa saw that on the big screen and celebrated. But the on-field decision stays. South African players' are unhappy with the decision.

Wicket right after the drinks break.

DRINKS! South Africa have done well to break the partnership between Cheteshwar Pujara and Virat Kohli. Cheteshwar Pujara was looking good in the middle, but could not hold on for too long. The hosts have still been disciplined with their bowling. Virat Kohli is looking strong and is hitting the right deliveries, he is playing with some positive intent and will be looking to stick around till the end to guide India to a healthy total.

KL Rahul and Mayank Agarwal started with some positive intent but lost their momentum a bit and that cost them their wickets. Rahul nicked one to the keeper and then Agarwal followed him in the very next over. Cheteshwar Pujara and Virat Kohli are looking good at the moment with the former who tends to play slow early on is scoring at a better rate than Kohli. There were many outside off deliveries but Kohli is not getting drawn to go after it and is allowing himself to take time and settle in. The Proteas are on the front foot at the moment and will look to continue the same after the break. The second session will start at 4:40 pm IST (11:10 am GMT). Do join us for the same.

Good session for South Africa. Probing lines and lengths from their bowlers have helped them pile the pressure on Indian batters. There were not many freebies given by pacers, they were disciplined in their bowling throughout. There was swing movement early on and they used it perfectly to stress the visitors and that helped them remove the openers for a cheap score.

Both the teams stride out and line up for their respective national anthems. It is India's first followed by South Africa's. We are done with all the formalities. The conditions are overcast and it was drizzling earlier but we are all set to go now. KL Rahul and Mayank Agarwal are the openers for India. The players take a knee against racism. Kagiso Rabada to start with the ball. Let's play...

We have the birthday boy with us, Rahul Dravid, India's Head Coach, says that he has turned one year older but it is nice to have so many messages from everyone. Adds that the wicket didn't do much in the last match but credit to South Africa as they batted really well. Says that it is a close series and it is an exciting last match. Tells that at this level you don't need any motivation after playing for your country. Hopes that the performance should be better than the last one and is looking forward to it. Mentions that they have experience in the batting line and bowling as well, all around the squad is balanced and hopes to be competitive throughout the contest.

Pitch Report - Hashim Amla and Vernon Philandar are down at the pitch. Philandar says that it's different here in South Africa, there is a little bit of grass, which will help the pacers. Also, there is a bit of moisture and it could be on the slower side.  Hashim Amla states there are bare patches on one end, and a bit more grass on the other end. Philander says that he would fancy his chances to bowl first, while Hashim Amla says that he would have liked to put a score on the board.

Dean Elgar, the skipper of South Africa says that they would have batted first as well. Says the conditions are overcast and adds that it is a big match for the whole nation. Says they have lost many big names but the youngsters are stepping up and these young ones do not have any scars and they come with a fresh mind. Apart from himself, who has some old-school mindset, the squad is pretty good. Informs they are going with the same XI. Informs that they have a balanced squad and is trusting his players

Virat Kohli, the skipper of India says that no one can control the weather. Adds that runs on this venue have always worked out well and they are looking forward to put some runs on the board. Mentions that he is fit and fine and he is back for this one. Further adds that there are two changes, he comes in for Hanuma Vihari and Umesh Yadav replaces Siraj. On being asked about his decision on choosing Umesh, he says that Umesh has been doing well and his performance has been good in his previous games. Concludes by saying that, Newlands is a beautiful stadium and the team is very excited.

South Africa (Unchanged playing XI) - Dean Elgar (C), Aiden Markram, Keegan Petersen, Rassie van der Dussen, Temba Bavuma, Kyle Verreynne (WK), Marco Jansen, Kagiso Rabada, Keshav Maharaj, Duanne Olivier, Lungi Ngidi.

India (Playing XI) - KL Rahul, Mayank Agarwal, Cheteshwar Pujara, Virat Kohli (C) (In for Hanuma Vihari), Ajinkya Rahane, Rishabh Pant (WK), Ravichandran Ashwin, Shardul Thakur, Mohammed Shami, Jasprit Bumrah, Umesh Yadav (In for Mohammed Siraj).
TOSS - India have won the toss and they have elected to BAT first!

Dean Elgar took blows on his body to help his team draw the series and their pace bowlers are proving lethal at their home surface. On the other side, India will be without Siraj and Ishant Sharma could make a comeback after a long time. The conditions are overcast in Cape Town, but let's hope the rain stays away. We can expect an exciting contest from both teams as South Africa will be looking to win in their own backyard while India will look for their first series win in South Africa. Stay tuned for the toss and other updates.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 1 of this intriguing final and third Test match between South Africa and India. The series is firmly poised at 1-1 and whoever wins here will clinch the series as well. The hosts are coming from behind and with the performance, they showcased at Johannesburg, the Proteas will be high on confidence. The good news for India is that Virat Kohli is back and ready to roar once again.
... Day 1, Session 1 ...

We are back for the third innings. KL Rahul and Mayank Agarwal walk out to the middle with their swords. South African players are seen to be in a huddle, before they take their respective fielding positions. Kagiso Rabada to steam in with the cherry. Here we go...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

South Africa get bundled out for 210 runs. Some valuable runs by the tail-enders cut down the deficit to 13 runs. Who else? It was Bumrah who gets his five-fer his seventh in Test cricket. Thakur chipped in with a wicket as well. But they could not end things as quickly as they would’ve liked too. Rabada and Olivier battled solidly in the middle, the former took some nasty body blows. The hosts fought till the very end but India would be really happy with their performance. They will come out to bat and hope they remain unscathed till the Stumps. But with the new ball, the hosts will certainly not make it easy for the Indian batters. Do join us in a short while.

A slight halt in play. Kagiso Rabada has been struck on the helmet. A mandatory concussion check will be done. The physio is out in the middle to do the needful. Hence the umpires have also signaled for a drinks break. India have sent back the sent-batter Petersen and now are attacking the bowlers. But Rabada and Olivier are fighting out really well in the middle and frustrating the Indian bowlers. India would hope they can take the remaining wickets before the hosts could cut down the deficit.

Length ball, on off. Rabada defends it to cover for a quick single.

A stifled appeal from Yadav but the umpire is unmoved. Back of a length, on the bodyline. Rabada looks to pull it away but misses. Yadav thinks it came off the gloves and puts in a loud appeal but the umpire is not interested.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! That's the wicket India were searching for and Jasprit Bumrah does the trick once again. A length ball, outside off. Keegan Petersen stands tall and looks to defend that but gets a thick outside edge to first slip. Cheteshwar Pujara at first slip, gets low, and grabs it comfortably. A perfect length, perfect line. Keegan Petersen's gritty innings comes to an end. Jasprit Bumrah is one wicket away from his five-fer!
Commentary.Howout: c Cheteshwar Pujara b Jasprit Bumrah

The final session is set to begin. The Indian players stride out to the middle. Followed by Keegan Petersen and Kagiso Rabada, the new man in who walk out to bat for the hosts. Jasprit Bumrah to complete his over.
... Day 2, Session 3 ...

South Africa are 7 down! They surely did not expect that to happen. The hosts lost Rassie van der Dussen early, but Bavuma and Petersen steadied the ship and added 47 runs together to put them on top. But the hosts were all over the place in the final hour of the session. They lost two wickets in one over and were under pressure since then. However, Keegan Petersen is still standing tall at the crease and adding crucial runs on the board, but he has no support at the other end. The Proteas would hope that he could hit some lusty blows in the final session of the day to close the gap with India. Do join us at 1900 IST (1330 GMT) to find out how things pan out.

India all the way! The visitors would definitely be the happier side at the end of this session. They have been exceptional with the ball. The bowlers have hit the right areas, and have grabbed the desired wickets. They clinched four wickets to put South Africa in trouble. Umesh Yadav struck early in the session and took the wicket of Rassie van der Dussen, who was looking uncomfortable at the crease. Shami followed up with two wickets in an over and put the hosts under pressure. Bumrah scalped his third wicket after knocking Marco Jansen just at brink of Tea.

OUT! TIMBER! Jasprit Bumrah does what he does best and gets his third wicket of the game. Brilliant by Bumrah. Until now, Bumrah was attacking Jansen with short deliveries but this time he bowls it on the stumps and Jansen pays the price. A length ball, around off, nipping in off the deck. Jansen looks to defend it out but misses and sees his off stump uprooted. Jasprit Bumrah wins this battle for sure and India go back as the happier side. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 2.
Commentary.Howout: b Jasprit Bumrah

Kyle Verreynne is tempted and he looks to drive it away. The ball takes the outside edge and flies low to the right of the keeper. Pant is quick to put in a dive to his right and gathers the ball before it lands on the field. India right on top now!
Commentary.Howout: c Rishabh Pant b Mohammed Shami

Temba Bavuma looks to defend it out and gets a thick outside edge. The ball flies towards the slip cordon. Virat Kohli there dives to his left to take a sharp catch. This is also his 100th catch in Test matches. This is what India wanted.
Commentary.Howout: c Virat Kohli b Mohammed Shami

But positively for the Proteas, Bavuma and Petersen have negotiated well and are well invested in the repair work. If this stand keeps on building the trajectory of the game can certainly change. India would like to take a couple of wickets before heading out for Tea.

India would be really happy with their performance with the ball but might feel they were unlucky as they got a lot of edges but did not find much success off it. Bumrah and Shami both bowled with fire and kept things tight. Bumrah did not take much time to have an impact and sent back Markram in the very first over. Yadav and Thakur combined well, as the former got a wicket of Maharaj but you can say they erred their lines and could not keep the batters under the pump. India would hope they can break this stand in the second session and get the momentum back to their side. Do join us at 1640 IST (1110 GMT) for another thrilling session of Test cricket.

A sigh of relief for the hosts! Maharaj who injured his hamstring at the end of Day 1, came in with a strap on his thigh and batted beautifully even after losing Markram on just the second delivery of the day. During his time out in the middle with Petersen, he was the aggressor in this stand before he fell out. Later Petersen showed good temperament and grew into his innings to stitch a crucial partnership with Rassie van der Dussen of 55 runs and remained unscathed till the Lunch break. Proteas would hope the pair can stick around for long in the next session as well with the deficit down to 123 runs.

What an intriguing session this one was! Both the teams fought really hard and, in the end, South Africa would be happy to see Keegan Petersen and Rassie van der Dussen walk out of the field at the end of the first session. While, India would be feeling hard done by.

The first session is set to begin. Virat Kohli leads his side onto the field. Followed by Aiden Markram and Keshav Maharaj who walk out with their blades. Jasprit Bumrah to steam in with the ball. Here we go...

Cheteshwar Pujara is down for a chat. He says there is enough in it for the bowlers. It is a very good cricketing pitch, even the batters can score on it. Mentions that the batters need to know what kind of shots to play, and once the batsman is set he can make it count. He could not do it, but Virat did very well. Adds that they should have scored 30-40 runs more, but they are very confident they can bowl well, they have one of the best bowling attacks in the world, and they can restrict South Africa. Concludes by saying that, if they bowl well, third innings it will be the best wicket to bat on, and they have to make sure to make it count and 275 is a good total on this pitch.

After their chase in the previous game, South Africa will be high on confidence and will be thinking they can take the lead from here, despite losing their skipper, Dean Elgar. We witnessed a Virat Kohli masterclass yesterday and now it’s upto the bowlers. A few early wickets in the first session will surely put India in the driver's seat. Will India put South Africa in trouble? Or will the hosts score big? Let’s find out. A thrilling first session awaits.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 2 of this exciting Test match between South Africa and India. We witnessed a fast-moving Day 1, a total of 11 wickets fell. Although the day belonged to South Africa, the visitors will be happy after picking up the prized scalp of Dean Elgar.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

Right. That is all from Day 1. We will be back for Day 2 on 12th January so do join us for the same. The day is scheduled to start at 2:00 pm IST (8:30 am GMT) but our buildup begins early on, so do join us for that. Till then, Adios!

India, on the other hand, have shown a decent batting performance. Virat Kohli was the lone wolf, who guided India past 200 runs. While India kept losing wickets in a cluster, Virat Kohli stood tall. He seemed like a different player today. He displayed his class and gave the bowlers something to bowl at. Cheteshwar Pujara did show some grit and resilience in the middle, but he failed to carry on. But, they have done well to grab an early wicket. Indian bowlers will not make it easy for South Africa to take the lead, even though they have an opportunity to go ahead.

After being asked to bowl first, South Africa have done a phenomenal job to bundle out India for a below-par score of 223. Kagiso Rabada was surely the leader of the pack. He managed to grab four wickets including that of the India, skipper, Virat Kohli. Marco Jansen too was exceptional and managed to grab three wickets. Ngidi and Duanne Olivier picked a wicket each, but they were very disciplined throughout the innings. Coming into bat, South Africa have lost their skipper early. Markram and Keshav Maharaj have done well to survive and they will be hoping to continue the same way.

End of a thrilling day of Test cricket. South Africa will be the happier side at the end of Day 1! A scintillating bowling performance from the hosts. But India have certainly ended the day on a high after grabbing the big wicket of Dean Elgar.

Full ball, angling on middle. Keshav Maharaj pushes it to mid on.
Pitches it up, on off, this is pushed to mid off.
On a length, on off. Keshav Maharaj blocks it on the off side. Survival time for him.
Another solid block from Aiden Markram and Maharaj will face the potential last over.
Very full, slanting on middle. Aiden Markram jams it out to the bowler.
Outside off. Left alone.
Fuller ball, on off. Aiden Markram blocks it to the leg side.
Angles a length ball, on off. Defended out.
Length ball, outside off. Aiden Markram leaves it alone.
Almost squared up but Keshav Maharaj defends it low and on the ground to the off side.
BEATEN! The ball whizzes past the blade. On a length, outside off. Keshav Maharaj looks to defend but misses.
Bangs a short ball, on middle. Keshav Maharaj sit under it.
A fuller ball, outside off. Keshav Maharaj leans and pushes it to deep extra cover. Two runs taken. He gets off the mark with that.

A slight halt in play. Not sure whether Keshav Maharaj is really struggling or it is just a tactic to waste time. Whatever it is, he is doing really well. The physio checks and we are ready to resume.

Quick single! Aiden Markram takes a single and gives the strike to the night-watchmen. On middle, this is hit to mid on where the fielder has a shy at the keeper's end but misses. With the reaction from the fielders behind the stump. It looked close.
This one lands outside off and shapes away. Aiden Markram leaves it alone.
Mohammed Shami comes into the attack.
Bumrah goes wide of the crease and angles it on middle. Maharaj gets his bat down in time and tucks it to mid-wicket. Keshav Maharaj survives...
On a length, on off. Blocked out.
Keshav Maharaj, the night watchman, walks in to bat at number 3.

OUT! TAKEN! What a delivery from Bumrah! Dean Elgar was facing some difficulties and Bumrah continued to bowl in that channel. On a length, angling around off. Dean Elgar is squared up as he looks to defend and gets a thick outside edge to first slip where Cheteshwar Pujara holds on to it.
Commentary.Howout: c Cheteshwar Pujara b Jasprit Bumrah

Commentary.Commentary: Length and on off, this is hit to gully.
EDGED! This is full and drifting, around off. Dean Elgar is squared up as he looks to push with soft hands and gets an outside edge to second slip who collects it on a bounce.
A length ball,angling on off, extra pace from Bumrah. Elgar defends it more off the inner half and back on the deck.

FOUR! Top-shot to end the over! An overpitched delivery, on middle. Aiden Markram drives it past mid on for a boundary. Too full and too straight on this occasion, and Markram makes full use of this one.
On a length, outside off. Aiden Markram leaves it alone.
Lenght ball, on middle. Aiden Markram shows the full face of his bat and blocks it out.
Good-length delivery, on middle. Aiden Markram pushes it uppishly straight down the ground for two runs.
A length ball, on the pads. Dean Elgar tucks it towards mid-wicket. A single taken.
Short of a length, outside off. Dean shoulders arms to it.
BEATEN! Good channel from Jasprit Bumrah! A length ball, angling around off, it holds its line. Aiden Markram looks to defend inside it but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Touch fuller, way outside off. Aiden Markram shoulders arms to it.
Fullish delivery, slanting on middle. Aiden Markram gets behind the line of the ball to keep it out.
On a length, on middle. Aiden Markram hops and blocks it out.
Full again but way outside off. Easy leave.
Full and angling on off. Blocked out on the off side.
Fuller ball, outside off. Elgar offers no shot to this one.
Length and on off. Dean Elgar defends it right under his eyes. Not much movement for Indian bowlers yet.
Dean Elgar is off the mark as well. Full and outside off, this is punched through covers for a brace.
Full, slanting across, outside off. Left alone.
South Africa and Aiden Markram are underway! A length ball, around off. Aiden Markram defends it off the outer half through point and gets a single.
Length and on off. Aiden Markram blocks it out.
Umesh Yadav will bowl from the other end.
BEATEN! A JAFFA! Jasprit Bumrah serves a length ball, shaping it away outside off. Dean Elgar looks to have a poke at it but gets beaten on the outside edge. A maiden to begin with!
Ouchh! Elgar is feeling the sting of the blow! A length ball, targeting the pads. Elgar misses his flick and gets hit between the thigh guard and front pad.
A length ball, angling across, outside off. Elgar taps it to point.
Serves a short ball, outside off. Elgar shoulders arms to it.
Full and on the pads, this is flicked to mid-wicket. Shardul Thakur there does really well to get low and stop it.
Bumrah starts with a length ball, on middle. Elgar blocks it out.

The final session of the day is set to begin. The Indian players stride out to the middle. Dean Elgar and Aiden Markram will open the batting for South Africa. Jasprit Bumrah will begin the proceedings with the ball. Here we go...
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

India though would not feel out of it. They managed to keep the hosts under 212 in the first innings and will back themselves to defend this. South Africa on the other hand, won the second Test chasing a score bigger than this one and will fancy their chances. Join us after the break for the reply.

The Indian batting was quite disappointing. Had it not been for Pant, they would have well and truly been out of the game. His 100 could well be the difference. None of the others even managed to cross the 30-run mark. Actually, except for Kohli and Pant nobody else got over 20. Quite disappointing and India would feel, they are 30 to 40 short of what could be called a par score.

Ngidi was the star in this session. He got three wickets in no time and got the South Africans back into the game. Rabada and Jansen then joined the party as they got rid of the tail quickly. Overall, South Africa will be very pleased with their effort with the ball. They were at it right from the start today. Jansen, Ngidi and Rabada have given their side a real chance to win this series.
An outstanding effort with the ball by South Africa in this session and they will surely enter the break as the happier side as they have to chase just the 212 runs.

OUT! CAUGHT! Keeping Bumrah on the crease did not go as planned. A full-length ball, outside off. Bumrah swings hard at it. The ball goes towards point off the outside edge. Temba Bavuma settles under it and takes the simplest of catches. INDIA END THEIR INNINGS AT 198/10. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 3.
Commentary.Howout: c Temba Bavuma b Marco Jansen

Commentary.Commentary: A full-length ball, on off. Bumrah lofts it over mid off. The batters take two runs. India could've taken a single here to keep Pant on strike but they think otherwise.
WIDE! A short ball, on leg. Bumrah looks to pull it away but misses. The umpire signals a wide due to height.
CLOSE! A slower, full-length delivery, just outside off. Bumrah looks to drive it away but misses. The ball sneaks under the blade and goes past the off pole.

Pant is not happy. He does not get the single of the last ball, that means Bumrah will face the next over. This was short and outside off. Pant comes down the track and slaps it down to cover from above his head. There is a fielder there who restricts Pant to get to the other end.
Short ball, outside off. Pant looks to chase it but misses.
Swing and a miss! A length ball, outside off. Pant looks to chase it but misses, as the ball bounces over the blade.
Short ball, outside off. Pant cuts it to point.
Length, on off, blocked out.
A length ball, outside off. Pant has no stroke to offer.
Back of a length, on off. Bumrah leaves it alone.
Back of a length, down leg. Bumrah ducks under it.

CENTURY FOR PANT! A knock to remember for the ages! Absolutely stunning! Single-handedly he is responsible for the score India are at right now. On a wicket where run scoring has not been easy, he has got his ton up in just the 133 balls. Could have been a lot more earlier had he not refused the amount of singles he has done in the last few overs because he’s batting with the tail. Coming to the ball it was a short ball, on off. pulled to fine leg for a single. An innings of great maturity. He played according to the situation, read the pitch well, took calculated risks and has reaped the rewards. Can he somehow take India’s lead to 250 now? He gets to the milestone by pulling this short ball down to fine leg. His teammates are on their feet applauding the effort. He takes off his helmet, raises the bat and soaks in the applause.
Length ball, on off. Pant blocks it out watchfully.
Pant tries to be aggressive now. A short ball, outside off. Pant comes down the track and looks to smash it away but misses.
Full length, on off. Pant gets low and looks to sweep it away but misses. He get hit on his pads and eventually rolls down on the ground.
A single now! Pant retains the strike this time. A short ball, on middle and leg. Pant works it to deep square leg for a single. He moves to 99 and will also retain the strike.
A sharp bouncer, on off. Pant stands back and looks to hook it away but misses.
Back of a length, outside off. Pant slaps it down to long off. But opts against the single.
Short ball, outside off. Pant cuts it to point.

FOUR! Fortune favours the brave. This is what India need and Pant is their last hope now. A full-length ball, on off. Pant gets under it and lofts it towards long off. Temba Bavuma runs in and puts in a dive forward but the ball goes through him and into the boundary.
Outside off, left alone.
Jasprit Bumrah is the last man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Mohammed Shami's stay comes to an end now! A short ball, on off. Shami stands tall and looks to pull it away. The ball flies off the outside edge towards the leg side. The short leg fielder, Rassie van der Dussen, moves to his right, settles under it and completes the catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Rassie van der Dussen b Marco Jansen

Commentary.Commentary: A single now! Pant is looking really sharp in the middle. A short ball, on off. Pant stays back and pulls it to deep square leg for a single. Shami has one ball to face.
Back of a length, outside off. Pant hangs back and cuts it to point.
Full-length ball, on off. Pant presses forward and blocks it out watchfully.
Length, on off, blocked out.

Review! South Africa have reviewed a caught behind decision. The replay rolls in. UltraEdge shows a flat line as the ball passes through the bat. The on-field decision stands. South Africa lose a review.

NOT OUT! Jansen comes around the wicket now. A full-length ball, down leg. Pant looks to flick it away but misses. Kyle Verreynne moves to his right and gathers the ball. He is jumping and appealing for caught behind. Dean Elgar takes the review. The UltraEdge show no bat is involved. Pant survives and the hosts lose a review here.
Good-length delivery, outside off. Shami has blocked that one out towards point.
On a length, around the hips. Shami tucks it past the short leg fielder. But they decide not to take any run.
Touch shorter, outside off. Pant hangs back and cuts it towards deep point. This time a single is taken.
Wide of off, on a length. Pant pushes it towards deep cover. No runs of that one.
Back of a length, around middle. Pant pulls it to square leg. No run taken.
On a length, width on offer. Pant cuts it away towards third man.
Fuller, around middle. Shami blocks it out on the leg side.
Outside off, on a length. Pant pushes it towards deep cover for a single. India now have a lead of 200 runs!
On a length, outside off. Pant shuffles across and taps it towards square leg for brace. Good batting by Pant!
Yorker length, on middle. Rishabh Pant jabs it out back to the bowler.
Touch fuller, outside off. Pant tries to be innovative here and looks to reverse-scoop that but fails to get any bat on it.
Back of a length, around middle. Pant pulls it to the fielder at deep mid-wicket. No run taken.
Marco Jansen (16-6-28-2) comes into the attack now.
Shami survives! Another length ball, on middle. Shami blocks it out watchfully.
Good-length delivery, around middle and off. Shami shows the full face of his bat and defends it out.
Wide of off this time, on a length. Pant cuts it towards deep point for a single. This brings Shami on strike for the last two balls.
Length, outside off. Pant stays in his crease and blocks it out.
WIDE! A slower bouncer, outside off. This one goes above the batter's head. Pant lets that go through. Wide signaled for height here.
Back of a length, around middle. Pant pulls it towards deep square leg.

DROPPED! A fuller ball, wide of off. Pant reaches out to it, and slashes but the ball goes off the top-edge. The ball flies towards deep point. Keshav Maharaj runs forward and dives forward to grab it but fails to pouch it cleanly. A sigh of relief for the Indians. A big chance for South Africa goes down.
A low full toss ball, down the leg side. Shami flicks it towards fine leg. Dot to end the over.
On a length, around middle again. Shami defends it out.
Length ball, around off. Mohammed Shami blocks it out.
Fuller, on off. Pant pushes it to point for a single.
NO BALL! Touch fuller again, outside off. Pant drives it towards mid off without any leg movement.
Fuller, outside off. Pant reaches out to drive that, loses his balance in the process. Another dot ball.

CRUNCHED! A length ball, nipping back in around off. Rishabh Pant advances down the ground and slashes this towards deep point. Also, the bat has flown away towards square leg. Pant cuts it away with all his power. But no runs off it as the fielder in the deep gathers it comfortably.
Back of a length, shaping from outside off. Mohammed Shami leaves it alone. End of a successful over by Kagiso Rabada.
Mohammed Shami is the new man in. Also, the physio is out. Pant looks to in some pain. His right elbow is hurting him.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! This time Kagiso Rabada gets him. Third time's a charm! Another length ball, shaping away a tad from outside off. Umesh Yadav looks to have a poke at it away from his body. The ball goes off the outside edge behind to the keeper. Kyle Verreynne takes another easy catch to dismiss Umesh Yadav. India are now 8 down and the lead is still not over 200! Kagiso Rabada gets his third wicket.
Commentary.Howout: c Kyle Verreynne b Kagiso Rabada

Commentary.Commentary: BEATEN again! Another length ball, outside off. Yadav, once again tries to block this but gets beaten.
Good length, on the pads. Yadav tucks it towards short leg.
BEATEN! This one is much close to the blade. On a length, outside off. Umesh Yadav, hangs back and looks to defend but gets beaten as the ball zips past the outside edge.
Swing and a miss! A length ball, shaping away from outside off. Umesh Yadav swings his bat hard at it, but gets beaten on the outside edge.
FOUR! Just the 13 away from a ton now. This is banged short and on middle, Pant pulls it over mid-wicket for a boundary. 10 runs to end the over.
SIX! That hits the ropes on the full! A strong hit by Pant to power himself into the 80s. This is short and on middle. Pant clears his front leg and slams it over long on. Goes all the way.
Loose! Short and outside off, Pant slashes with no foot movement. He is beaten.
Shorter and on off, defended.

Looks to be expansive! The thought was right, he just did not get the length he wanted. Pant makes room. He was expecting a short one and he wanted to upper cut it over the slip cordon but the bowler bowls a length ball. He cuts it to deep point. No run taken.
Shorter and on middle, blocked.
He has to get bat in that! On middle, this is pushed to mid on.
Goes short, Yadav ducks under it.
Back of a length and on off, this is played to gully.
Outside off, left alone.
That is how the last ball should have been played! With the full face of the bat. Like Yadav did here. On off, Yadav shows the maker's name and plays it to mid on.
Umesh Yadav walks out to the middle now.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Ngidi has another one and South Africa have stormed back into the game in this session. They are now into the bowler's and the lead for India is not even 200. Not sure where Thakur was looking to play this. It is full and outside off. He looks to work it on the leg side. The ball seams away a touch. It goes off the outside edge and the keeper, Kyle Verreynne, makes no mistake.
Commentary.Howout: c Kyle Verreynne b Lungi Ngidi

Commentary.Commentary: On off, Pant defends it to the leg side.
On middle, this is worked to mid on.
Well played! Shorter and on middle, Thakur works it by taking one hand off the handle. Handles the extra bounce well. It goes through square leg for one.
Outside off, left alone.
Bangs it short again and on off, this is guided to point.
FOUR! Put away! Width on offer and Thakur cashes in. Short and outside off, this is flayed away through point. Boundary. Good start for India after the break.

DRINKS! South Africa have come back stronger in the second session. They have done well to pick up the prized wicket of Virat Kohli. India have lost Ravichandran Ashwin as well. But, Rishabh Pant continues to keep the scoreboard ticking. Shardul Thakur too can put on a great show. India will be hoping these two stick around till Tea. India have a lead of 178 runs now.
A dot to end! Good stuff from Ngidi. Making the batter play. On off, kept out.
Again on middle, Pant plays it onto the ground.
On middle, this is kept out.
Two taken! On middle, this is worked through mid-wicket for two.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
On a length and on middle, this is kept out.
Fuller and on off, Thakur strokes it to mid off.
Back of a length and outside off, left alone.
Just short! Another one angling into the pads, Thakur flicks stylishly but uppishly, it lands just short of the man at mid-wicket.
Well played! This lands on off and then comes back in. Thakur plays it late and he works it with the movement to mid-wicket.
Bangs it short and on middle, Shardul nudges it to square leg.
Shorter and on the body, this is worked on the leg side for one. Duanne is down on the ground as he lost his footing in his followthrough.
Duanne Olivier (6-1-20-0) is back on!
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Thakur leaves it alone for the keeper. A really good over by Ngidi, just a run and a wicket off it.
Full-length ball, outside off. Thakur presses forward and defends it out off the outer half towards gully.
Back of a length, on the fourth stump line. Thakur shoulders his arms at it.
Shardul Thakur is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ravichandran Ashwin could not keep his composure and India lose their sixth wicket. Full-length ball, outside off. Ravichandran Ashwin throws his blade at it. It was well outside off for him to leave it but Ngidi is successful in enticing the batter here. The ball goes off the outside edge towards gully. Marco Jansen takes a sharp catch there. India have lost two wickets in quick succession.
Commentary.Howout: c Marco Jansen b Lungi Ngidi

Commentary.Commentary: Full-length ball, outside off. Pant leans in and drives it to sweeper cover. The batters take a single. They were looking for two but the fielder was quick to get to the ball.
Outside off, left alone by Pant.
On the pads, Ashwin defends it to mid-wicket.
Good length, on off. Ashwin hangs back and blocks it out solidly.
Fuller, on middle and leg. Pant hangs back and clips it to mid-wicket for another single. The lead moves to 174 runs now.
Back of a length, around the hips. Ashwin hops and clips it to deep square leg for a single.
Fuller, on off. Ashwin defends it to cover.
Length ball, on the pads. Pant clips it to square leg for a single.
Length ball, just outside off, nips in a bit late. Ashwin leaves it alone for the keeper watchfully.

JUST OVER! Good-length ball, outside off. Some extra bounce off the deck with some away movement. Ashwin stays behind and swings his blade at it. The ball takes the outside edge and flies towards slip cordon. Aiden Markram at second slip flies as well. He gets his fingers to it but could not pouch it this time. The batters take two before the fielder cuts it out.
A length ball, on the pads. Ashwin stays back and defends it out to mid-wicket off his gloves.
Three dots in a row! Swing and a miss this time! A length ball, outside off. Ashwin tries to drive it on the up but misses and gets beaten on the outside edge.
A length ball, around off, nips in off the deck. Ashwin comes forward and looks to flick it away but misses and gets hit high on the pads.
Short ball, on off. Ashwin stays back and punches it to point.

Full length, on off. Pant defends it back to the bowler with the full face of the blade. Jansen collects the ball and throws it towards the batter. Pant was holding his pose and hence was able to get behind the line of the throw and defends it out again. Some heat growing between these two now.
Full-length ball, on the fourth stump line. Pant shuffles across and defends it out watchfully.
Back of a length, outside off. Pant shoulders his arms at it.
Full, on middle and leg. Pant defends it to the leg side.
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Pant leaves it alone for the keeper.
Full, outside off. Pant defends it out solidly.
Marco Jansen (14-5-25-2) is brought back into the attack.
Length ball, on off stump. Ashwin stays inside the crease and defends it to cover off the outer half.
FOUR! Nicely played. Ashwin gets off the mark with a boundary. This is typical Ashwin. On a length, on off. Ashwin hangs back and punches it through covers for a boundary.
BEATEN! Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away a hint. Ashwin stays inside the crease and looks to punch it away but misses. The ball zips past the outside edge.
Full length, on off. Ashwin defends it back to the bowler.
Ravichandran Ashwin comes to the crease now.

OUT! CAUGHT! Virat Kohli has been so watchful but for once he chases the ball outside off and it costs him his wicket. Lungi Ngidi gets the big fish and this is the breakthrough the hosts were looking for. A full-length ball, outside off. Kohli hangs back and looks to go for the booming drive but only manages to outside edge it to the slip cordon. Aiden Markram leaps and takes a sharp catch at second slip. Kohli is not happy with himself as he trudges back to the pavilion. Have to say luck isn’t completely on Kohli’s side. He has worked so hard for his runs, both in the first and in the second innings but his first mistake sees his downfall. Being a batter you need luck to go your way and at the moment, luck isn’t on Kohli’s side. Can South Africa now build on this?
Commentary.Howout: c Aiden Markram b Lungi Ngidi

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, outside off. Pant dabs it to point for a single.
Much flatter this time, outside off. Kolhi defends it out. 15 runs off that over!
Loopy ball, around off. Kolhi presses forward and blocks it out.
Another short ball, this one turn in sharply, Pant pushes it towards cover for a single.
Shorter now, outside off. Pant hangs back and cuts that past point for a brace. This is good batting from Pant! 150 up for India now!
SIX! Back-to-back sixes now! Another fuller ball, around off. Pant shimmies down the ground and tonks it over long off for a biggie. That's come from the middle of the bat as well.
SIX! Pant is on the attack against the spinner here. A loopy ball, around middle. Pant gets down and sweeps this towards deep mid-wicket for a biggie. The lead now crosses the 150 mark.
Length, outside off. Virat Kohli offers no shot to that.
Angling this one in from outside off, on a good length, Kohli gets across and defends it out.
Another length ball, outside off, at 135 clicks. Kohli shoulders his arms at it.
Good-length delivery, on middle. Kohli shows the full face of his bat and blocks it out.
BEATEN! A length ball, outside off. Kohli, on back foot, looks to block that but gets beaten as the ball zips past through the outside edge.
Angling it from outside off, Pant pushes it to point and scampers through to the other end.
Flighted delivery, fuller, outside off Virat Kohli has blocked that one solidly.
Quicker this time, outside the off pole again. Kohli hangs back and defends it out.
Touch fuller again, outside off. Kohli pushes this to point.
Change of angle for the right-hander. Keshav Maharaj goes around the wicket, serves a full and loopy ball. Kohli leans and blocks it out.
Fuller, outside off. Pant drives it towards deep cover for a single.
Pant decides to take him on! A loopy, full delivery. Pant shimmies down the pitch and drills it down the ground.
Good length, on the pads. Pant tucks it towards square leg for a single. He retains the strike.
Another length delivery, outside off. Pant shows the full face of his bat and blocks it out,
Lungi Ngidi goes around the wicket to the left-hander, serves a length ball, around off. Pant, on back foot, defends it out.

LEG BYE! Lungi Ngidi serves another length ball, darting it on the thigh pads this time. Virat Kohli misses his flick. The ball deflects off his thigh pad and rolls towards fine leg. The batters steal a leg bye.
Good-length delivery, shaping in a tad from outside off. Kohli lets that go through.
A length ball, outside off. Virat Kohli will watch it sail through to the keeper.
Lungi Ngidi to bowl from the other end.
Quicker again, around the off pole. Pant stays in his crease and blocks it out.
Shorter, tad quicker. Pant, on back foot, pushes it towards mid-wicket.
Wide of off, very full. Pant advances down the track and cuts it towards point. Does not find the gap here.
Flatter, on middle. Virat Kohli hangs back and taps it towards the diving mid-wicket fielder for a single.
Fuller, on middle. Pant presses forward and pushes it towards mid-wicket for a single.
Nice start! A loopy ball, around off. Pant leans and looks to defend but gets an inside edge towards short leg.
The second session is set to begin. The South African players stride out to the middle. Followed by Kohli and Pant who walk out with their swords. Keshav Maharaj to start with the ball. Here we go...
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

India, on the other hand, were in trouble very early. After losing Pujara and Rahane in quick succession. Virat Kohli, is displaying his masterclass once again, he has been disciplined at the crease, tackling the short balls well and attacking the freebies. Pant, too has been exceptional. He did not get tempted and chose his shots really well. He brought up his 8th half-century and has played a responsible innings here.  The duo have put together an unbeaten 72-run stand. Will South Africa make a come back? Or will the visitors keep carrying their sublime effort with the blade? We will find out soon. Do join us for the second session at 1640 IST (1110 GMT).

The hosts started off brilliantly, Marco Jansen grabbed the wicket of Pujara in his very first over of the day. In the very next over Rabada chipped in by sending back Rahane early to the hut. But since then, they have allowed the Indian batters to score freely. Although Jansen and Rabada did trouble the Indian skipper, with their short balls, but were not rewarded for the same. Coming into the second session, they would be hoping to grab quick wickets and not let India get away with a healthy lead.

A thrilling first session of Test cricket. The first hour of the match belonged to the hosts, while the second hour was truly India's. The visitors hold a slight edge over the Proteas. South Africa got rid of Pujara and Rahane early, but Kohli and Pant have kept the scoreboard ticking. India now lead by 143 runs at the end of the first session.
Fuller and on middle, this is played back to the bowler. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 3!
Shorter and on the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Outside off, left alone.

TWO! Fifty for Rishabh Pant! That is a superb innings! Yes, he has got it up in just the 58 balls but by no means has this been the careless Rishabh Pant we have seen in this series so far. We do not mean he has been very cautious, he has played his shots but he has selected the right balls. He's shown great maturity and has really dug his side out of the grave here. Still some way to go though. He gets a full ball on the pads, he works it through mid-wicket for two. Also, this is a much-needed knock for India. This innings from Pant, not only does wonders for him and his team but also for Kohli. Because of the speed Pant is scoring at, quite a lot of pressure is released of the Indian skipper.
Shorter and on the middle pole, defended.
Back of a length and on off, Pant stands tall and blocks.
On middle, defended.
Shorter now and on the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Steps out again, this time too he gets quite close to the pitch of the ball, ends up working it to mid-wicket.

SIX! Pant would have surely had his heart in his mouth there! He comes down the track, gets a little too close to the pitch of the ball. Still goes ahead with the shot, hits it flat but away from long on for a biggie.
Shorter and on middle, Pant works it to mid-wicket.
Tossed up on middle, defended.
The physio is out. Pant looks to be in some pain as he got hit on his finger a while ago. The physio is nursing it and confirms Pant is alright to continue.
Another delivery which is not on the stumps, not played at.
Outside off, left alone.
Angled into the pads, this is worked towards mid-wicket.
On off, Kohli blocks.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.

A single as this is worked through mid-wicket for one.

On middle, Kohli blocks it out.

On a length, just outside off, it moves away furhter. Left alone.
Angled into the middle pole, Kohli plays it right under his eyes and back to the bowler.

Fuller and on middle, Kohli shows the full face of the bat and plays it back to the bowler.

Closer to the off pole this time, Kohli shuffles across and plays it to covers.

Yet again on off, kept out nicely.
Attacks the off pole, Kohli gets right behind the line and plays it to covers.
Short again, this is worked towards mid-wicket for one.

DRINKS! We have witnessed an exciting first hour of Test cricket. South Africa have done well to pick up two wickets early in the day. But, Virat Kohli is still standing tall and playing another gritty innings. Pant at other the end is not getting too tempted but at the same time, he is adding valuable runs to the scoreboard. India now have a lead of 103 runs and they would like the current pair to remain unscathed till the Lunch break.
Length ball, outside off. Pant waits and opens the face of the bat late to push it towards point.

Back of a length, outside off. Kohli leaves it alone for the keeper.

Back-of-a-length delivery, outside off, angled across the left-hander. Pant shoulders his arms at it.

Full, on the pads. Pant flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.

Length, on off. Pant defends it out watchfully.
Two more! Full length, outside off. Pant leans in and drives it through covers. Pant calls for two instantly and gets it easily.
Short ball, outside off. Pant stands back and pulls it to deep mid-wicket. There is protection in the deep and the batters take two comfortably.

Was that a nick or a late swing? Back of a length, outside off, shaping away. Kohli looks to chase it but pulls his blade back in time. Kyle Verreynne dives to his right but fails to gather the ball. Anyways it wouldn't have matterd as it was a late shape away and did not get any bat on it.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! A huge appeal for a caught behind! The umpire initially says not out. But, South Africa take the review and the decision has to be overturned. OUT! TAKEN! What a start for South Africa! Marco Jansen strikes on his second ball! An absolute blinder by Keegan Petersen. Back of a length, down the leg side, a bit of extra bounce. Cheteshwar Pujara was looking to leave that one, but the deflects of the top of his bat and flies towards the leg slip. Keegan Petersen there dives to his right and takes an absolute stunner of a catch. On Day 2, Jasprit Bumrah did the same for a India, a wicket off the second ball and now Marco Jansen achieves the same feat. The hosts couldn't have asked for a better start.
Commentary.Howout: c Keegan Petersen b Marco Jansen

The first session is set to begin. Virat Kohli and Cheteshwar Pujara walk out with their blade for India. The South African players are seen to be in a huddle before they take their respective fielding positions. Marco Jansen to start with the ball. Here we go...

PITCH REPORT - Sunil Gavaskar is down for the pitch report. He says that it is a moving day and things could move rapidly. There is a bit of wear and tear near the good length area. It will be a little difficult to bat on. Therefore the bowlers will be in the game once again. Also says that it will be good to see how Kohli, Pujara and Rahane handle things from here.

Shardul Thakur is in for a spot interview. He says the game is evenly poised and now it is totally a second innings game. Adds that it is a proper cricketing pitch and has a lot to offer with three days in hand. Mentions, he just focuses on creating an impact and help his side in winning the game. Says, the players have talked about the pitch a lot, there is a lot to offer for the bowlers but if a batsman settles in really well, on can take the game to its head. On being asked about the target in mind, he says, over 300 runs should be a solid target in any Test match.

The hosts on the other hand, know India have the upper hand, but with Rabada and Jansen sending back the Indian opening pair gives them a glimmer of hope. They would be itching to come out on the field and run riots with the ball to restrict India to a chasable target. The bowlers need to remain patient for the Proteas and would know that a single spell can get them back in this match. An enthralling session of Test cricket awaits.

On Day 2, we saw the deck was helping the bowlers with some extra bounce and pace as compared to the first day. But if a batter is in the zone at the crease, he can make the most it. India have Kohli and Pujara in the middle now and would hope they can bat for as long as possible.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 3 of the final Test match between South Africa and India. The visitors bowled superbly on day 2 to bundle out the Proteas for 210. And were able to swell their lead to 70 runs with 8 wickets still in hand. India would hope bat the hosts out of the match.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

Right. That is all from Day 2. South Africa need to remain patient with the ball and just keep applying the pressure on the India batters. India have an experienced pair at the crease and would hope they can extend the lead and take the game away from the hosts. This game has moved at a really good pace, as we head into the moving day of Test cricket, Day 3. The action will begin at 1400 IST (0830 GMT). But as you all know our build-up begins early. Do join us to find out who things pan out. Till then, goodbye and take care!

South Africa, on the other hand, will be disappointed with their batting performance. Keegan Petersen was the lone warrior who fought the battle well, but could not hold on till the end. His innings of 72 gave the hosts something to smile about. The tail-enders did wag a little, which helped South Africa to a total of 210. Later, Rabada started off well with the ball, and picked an early wicket of Agarwal. Jansen followed up quickly with the prized wicket of KL Rahul. They have leaked a lot of runs since then and allowed the Indian batters to score freely with the new ball. They will be hoping to bowl a little tighter tomorrow and not let India get away with a heavy lead and make their task difficult with the blade later on in the game.

The visitors displayed a terrific show with the ball. Jasprit Bumrah was certainly the leader of the pack. He scalped his 7th Test five-wicket haul and demolished the South African batting lineup. Umesh Yadav and Mohammed Shami were exceptional as well. They were disciplined with their lines and lengths and troubled the South African batters, they were rewarded with two wickets each. Coming into bat, India lost their openers in quick succession, but since then Kohli and Pujara have done well to rebuild the innings. They kept the runs ticking and ended the day with a healthy lead of 70. The duo will look to continue the same way coming into Day 3.

India on top at the end of Day 2! A tremendous display of fast bowling by India helped them bundle out South Africa for just 210 runs and have ended the day with a lead of 70 runs. South Africa will be gutted with their batting performance but they will be mighty pleased with their effort with the ball, as they were able to send back the Indian openers cheaply.

Keegan Petersen is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH and the PLAYER OF THE SERIES. He says that it will take a couple of hours to sink in, but he is feeling happy and emotional. Adds that he took every little positive from each innings he played. It has been a tough journey for him, it has been difficult in different conditions. He says that, It's not been easy coming to Test cricket, there have been challenging wickets to play on, so it has been tough. Mentions that they knew it was always going to be difficult against top bowling attack, but they had a tough mindset. Concludes by saying that he has enjoyed every bit of his innings.

Dean Elgar, the victorious skipper, is in for a chat. He says that they are pretty elated. Mentions that he couldn't be more proud of the group and the guys have responded exceedingly well after the first loss. Tells that one needs to show immense character in these kind of conditions and 60 wickets in three Tests is a tough challenge for the bowlers but they bowled really well and it was unreal to see some performances. Says that he is extremely proud of the team. Adds that it helps to have a group that really doesn't have any big names, the guys just played well and played as a team. Mentions that he laid a few challenges, even to some senior players but it was great to see them take the message and be on board. Says that they have played as a unit and they have grown massively as a group in the last two Tests. States that if one needs to be No.1 someday in Test cricket, one needs to beat the best in the world. Says he is really happy with how things panned out in the end. Also says that they are by no means like a finished article and he is already focusing on the next series. Informs that there are still a few negatives that they need to work on. On Keegan Petersen, he says that he responded really well after the first Test and has shown great character. Also says that he has been brilliant in the domestic circuit for a while now and it's great to see him do so well in these last two Tests. Ends by saying that he's willing to learn more and more and a team needs a player like that who shows great character.

Virat Kohli, the Indian skipper, is in for a chat. He says, that he thinks it's a great spectacle of Test cricket for everyone. It was a hard-fought series. But South Africa have done well. They were able to capitalize on important hours and were absolutely the deserving winners at the end. Adds that one of the challenges faced during tours are to capitalize on momentum when it is on their side. Whenever they have done that, they have won games. But when they haven't done so, they have lost matches. Mentions that batting was the issue for their side, and South Africans have done well with the ball in these conditions, and yes, batting collapse is an issue and they will work upon that. On being asked what were the things he was happy about, he says that KL Rahul and Mayank Agarwal batted well, Pant's century was special and the win at centurion was special too.

But once again, Jansen and Rabada ran riot with the ball and sent back the opening pair cheaply at the end of Day 2. India would've loved to put up a target of 300 runs, but on the moving day, India lost two wickets within the opening 10 minutes of the morning session, in the form of Pujara and Rahane. It was Pant who played an aggressive innings but not relentless to notch-up his first Test ton against South Africa and set up a target just over 200 runs. India though managed to get a couple of wickets in the final session of Day 3. There were some decisions that the Indians were not happy with and due to lapse of concentration at certain phases might've costed them this series.

Earlier in the game, a vital contribution with the blade by Kohli and Pujara made sure India get 223 runs on the board in the first innings. As South African pacers were on the money and Rabada led the attack with his four-fer. It was the same story for the hosts when they came out to bat, as Keegan Petersen showed composure in the middle and made sure to help his side to get to 210 runs before India bundled them out and had a small lead in hand coming into the third innings.

Best teams fight till the very end, they say. But the body language of India was really low after they came out to field post the Lunch break. Also, surprisingly Kohli went with a combination of Ashwin and Yadav, and South African batters made sure to waste no time and took full advantage of it. Indians started the morning session really well. Their bowlers asked a lot of questions but the batters, had a rub of green, and India could only take a single wicket in the morning session through Lord Shardul Thakur. This wicket gave the visitors a glimmer of hope but South Africa were up to the task and took the game away from India comfortably.

What a revelation Keegan Petersen has been for South Africa. He has been exceptional in this series and that too against a strong bowling attack. In the morning session, Petersen came out with Rassie van der Dussen and saw off the first hour of the session quite comfortably and racked up good amount of runs after Petersen was dropped by Pujara in the slips. But Petersen yet again missed out on his Test century and holed out at 82. Later, Bavuma came to the crease and batted with great composure along with Rassie van der Dussen and remained unscathed till Lunch. After the break, South Africa wasted no time and scored runs at a brisk rate and chased the target within 45 minutes to seal the series.

South Africa take a 2-1 lead and win this Test series. What a turnaround this has been for the Proteas. Winning two back-to-back games to make the series theirs, who would've thought? The South African dressing room are up and celebrating. This Test had everything, drama, emotions, comebacks. Both the teams gave their all but, in the end, the hosts maintain their domination at home and India would be disappointed as they were not able to snatch the series even after winning the first Test match. Let's not forget about the World Test Championship point table. South Africa take the fourth spot after this victory and India slip down a spot and are now 5th on the point table.

The first session is set to begin. Indian players stride out to the middle. Followed by Keegan Petersen and Rassie van der Dussen, the new man in at number 4, who walk out to bat for the Proteas. Jasprit Bumrah to complete his over. Here we go...

PITCH REPORT - Sunil Gavaskar is near the deck. He says, the pitch has got down a little bit. There is a spot near the 8m mark, but when the ball comes around the 6m area, there is something on offer for the bowlers. It should be an interesting day of cricket.

South Africa on the other hand, were sensational and ruled Day 3. First, their pacers produced a lethal spell and bundled out India for 198. It was Lungi Ngidi who worked his magic in the second session and bagged three wickets. Jansen was the pick of the bowler with four wickets, while Rabada took 3 scalps. Chasing 212 , the hosts lost Aiden Markam for just 16 while Dean Elgar departed at the stroke of Stumps. With Keegan Petersen unbeaten on 48 and with 8 wickets in hand, the home side will fancy their chances for the win which will also seal the series for them. But a couple of early wickets in today's first session and things could turn around pretty quickly, you never know. An enthralling day of Test cricket awaits.

The moving day for India didn't turn out to be a great one as India were bowled out for 198, but the day turned out to be a great one for Rishabh Pant as out of those 198, 100 were scored by him. He became the first Asian wicketkeeper to notch up a ton on the South African soil and thanks to his ton, India set up a target of 212 runs. Once again, it was Shami and Bumrah who struck in the final session on Day 3 and the Indians would know that a wicket or two can change the trajectory of the game.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 4 and what should be the final day of the third and the last Test between India and South Africa. The equation is pretty simple for both teams. South Africa need 111 runs while India need 8 wickets to win their first Test series in South Africa. Let's see how the day pans out and which team wins the series.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

We cannot emphasize the importance of the first session on Day 4. Whichever team comes out on top before Lunch on Day 4 will have a big advantage. If India can get another couple of quick wickets, they will sense their first-ever Test series win in South Africa. But, if the next pair for South Africa can put up a 50-plus stand then the hosts will have a big advantage in the chase. It has been a Test in which not a single moment has been dull and Day 4 promises to be no different. Do join us for the same at 1400 IST (0830 GMT) for the first ball and also for the buildup which begins earlier. Till then, take care and goodbye!

We have witnessed so many comebacks in this Test match by both the sides and right at the stroke of Stumps, Bumrah puts his hand up and gets his side back in the equation after a prized scalp of Elgar. India started brilliantly and it was Shami who drew the first blood. India were not happy after a lbw decision went against them, after South Africa took the review and must have lost some concentration post that, which led to leaking a few extra runs and India won't be happy about it. India need more 8 wickets to mark a historic win in South Africa. Also, lets keep in mind, only thrice a team has chased down a target above 200 runs in Cape Town.

A really good session for the hosts until the wicket of their skipper. South Africa came out to bat with the right intention to chase down a target of 212 runs. Markram was the aggressor while Elgar was being watchful initially. Although, Markram went chasing for a few deliveries outside off and it costed him his wicket. Petersen joined Elgar in the middle, the runs came in at a slow rate initially. But Elgar made sure to make the most of his reprieve and both the batters scored runs at a brisk rate and 100 was up for the hosts in no time. But in the end, Elgar lost his wicket at the stroke of Stumps and that would hurt South Africa a lot.

What a day! What a day of Test cricket! Things are still neck and neck between these two sides and one hour of a dominant display by either side could put them well on top. The game has been dominated by pacers and Day 3 was no different. 10 wickets fell and we have a cracking finish coming up in the next two days.
